\subsection{Structures and Stability of the $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(15 \mathrm{1T5})^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(15 \mathrm{15} 5)_{2}{ }^{2+}$.}
The geometrical optimization for the $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(15 \text { TC5 })^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(15 \mathrm{TC} 5)_{2}{ }^{2+}(\mathrm{An}=\mathrm{U}, \mathrm{Np}, \mathrm{Pu}$, Am and $\mathrm{Cm}$ ) complexes have been explored. The $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(15 \mathrm{TC} 5)_{2}{ }^{2+}$ are unstable with a large imaginary frequency, leading to the formation of the $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(15 \mathrm{TC} 5)^{2+}$ shown in Figure $2 . \mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}{ }^{2+}$ prefers coordination by one rather than two 15TC5; this is considered as due to a weak bonding interaction of metal and sulfur atoms and large steric repulsion between two 15TC5 ligands. In contrast to the "side-on" structure of $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(12 \mathrm{TC} 4)^{2+}$ or "double decker" structure of $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(12 \mathrm{TC} 4)_{2}{ }^{2+}$, the ground state structures of the $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(15 \mathrm{TC} 5)^{2+}$ is a "standing" structure, in which the actinyl coordinates to all five $\mathrm{S}$ atoms with the average An-S distance decreasing from $2.931 \AA$ in $\mathrm{An}=\mathrm{U}$ to $2.902 \AA$ in $\mathrm{An}=\mathrm{Cm}$ (Table 3). This variation is attributed to the relativistic contraction of the An ionic radius. As was found for our previously studied oxo-crown complex, $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(15 \mathrm{C} 5)^{2+}(\mathrm{An}=\mathrm{U}, \mathrm{Np}, \mathrm{Pu}, \mathrm{Am}$ and $\mathrm{Cm})$, the $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}{ }^{2+}$ is similarly trapped in the center of 15TC5 with a longer An-S distance than the range of the An-S covalent single-bond lengths estimated by the sum of the self-consistent covalent radii derived by Pyykkö[69]. The calculated $\mathrm{An}-\mathrm{O}_{\mathrm{yl}}$ distances in $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(15 \mathrm{TC} 5)^{2+}$ decrease from uranium (average $\mathrm{U}-\mathrm{O}$ distance $\approx 1.789 \AA$ ), to americium, whereas the average An-O bond length is around $1.765 \AA$, and then increase up to curium, whereas the average An-O bond lengths are around $1.775 \AA$, as the results of balance between the contraction in atomic radii and bonding feature. Consistent with that of $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(12 \mathrm{TC} 4)^{2+}$, the well-known change from d-type dominance in charge of $\mathrm{An}=\mathrm{O}$ bonding and then to f-type behavior is labeled as the americium turn, a phenomenon that is caused by f-orbital energy-decrease and f-orbital localization with increase of both nuclear charge and oxidation state, and a non-linear variation of effective f-electron population across the actinide series.[70]

