\subsection{Structures and Stability of the $\mathrm{AnO}_{2}(18 \mathrm{1T6})^{2+}$.}
As for 15 TC5, $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(18 \text { TC6 })_{2}{ }^{2+}$ is unstable relative to decomposition to $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(18 \mathrm{TC} 6)^{2+}$ and 18TC6. The optimized structures of the $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(18 \mathrm{TC6})^{2+}$ (An $=\mathrm{U}, \mathrm{Np}$, Pu, Am and Cm) complexes are similar and displayed in Figure 3. The An-S distances are longer than $3.0$ Å (Table 4), indicating a weaker interaction between An and $\mathrm{S}_{18 \mathrm{TC} 6}$ than between $\mathrm{An}$ and $\mathrm{S}_{12 \mathrm{C} 4}$ or $\mathrm{S}_{15 \mathrm{C} 5}$, which is confirmed from average Mayer bond order value of $0.3,0.4$ and $0.5$ for $A n-S_{18 C 6}, A n-S_{15 C 5}$, and $A n-S_{12 C 4}$, respectively. The turning-point of $\mathrm{An}-\mathrm{O}_{\mathrm{yl}}$ bond lengths occurs at $\mathrm{An}=\mathrm{Am}$, in agreement with the above results in $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(12 \mathrm{C} 4)^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}(15 \mathrm{TC5})^{2+}$, and shifted up from the turn at $\mathrm{Pu}$ in the oxygen-containing complexes, which is consistent with the appearance of the turn at $\mathrm{AmO}_{2}{ }^{2+}$ in isolated actinyls (Table 5), indicating weak ligand field effect of sulfur on $\mathrm{An}^{\mathrm{VI}} \mathrm{O}_{2}{ }^{2+}$.

